title: Court Watch Training- Virtual
description:
Court watching is a tactic to raise public awareness about our current legal system and also to hold the system accountable through witnessing, documenting, and sharing out. This is a powerful and critical tool for organizing because so much harm is never witnessed and then goes unchecked! Court watching is a tool of PEOPLE POWER against those in power!

MN Freedom Fund's court watching program specifically watches bail hearings in Hennepin and Ramsey Counties. We are hoping to raise awareness about the injustices and disparities in this specific legal system moment. We want to establish a regular presence in court to hold the system players accountable and inspire more passion for local pre-trial changes! This training will be on how to court watch with MFF and then we'll have shifts for you to sign up for right away!

No prior experience needed!

title: Sister District South Bay & Friends Phonebank!
description:
Join Sister District South Bay on Saturdays at eleven to help our candidate, Lily Franklin, keep Virginia blue! A former high school math teacher and Chief of Staff for VA Delegate Sam Rasoul, Lily Franklin has long been a dedicated advocate for affordable housing, accessible childcare, and quality education. Help us elect Democratic challenger Lily Franklin to defend and expand our one seat majority in the Virginia House of Delegates!

After flipping the VA House of Delegates in 2023 by 975 votes, we must protect our Democratic majority to continue safeguarding democracy, especially with the growing threats coming from the federal government. Keeping the Dem majority ensures that Virginia remains a firewall against right-wing extremism and a leader in expanding economic opportunity, protecting freedoms, and defending democracy. A strong performance in Virginia this year will not only protect and expand the rights of Virginians but also generate national momentum, inspiring Democratic successes in the 2026 midterms. 


**Why phonebank:** The data proves it: phone banking is THE BEST volunteering option for remote voter contact. We identify supporters and let them know why their vote matters, speak with undecided voters, and recruit local volunteers. Every call helps us clean our lists, which makes for a faster, more efficient phonebank!

**Come one, come all:** No experience necessary. Each Zoom phonebank includes training and check-ins for first-timers (experienced callers can jump right in). We'll share successes and address questions throughout, all while contacting voters in crucial state legislative races. Our veteran phonebank leaders will help you get comfortable, increase your effectiveness, and make sure you have a great experience.

**Virginia is having a general election in 2025, and keeping the majority in the House of Delegates is crucial.**

After flipping the VA House of Delegates in 2023 by 975 votes, we must protect our Democratic majority to continue safeguarding democracy, especially with the growing threats coming from the federal government. title: PETITION: Eliminate Dallas Parking Minimums
description:
In a time of rising housing prices and climate disasters, we must re-evaluate how the space in our city is used. Cities like Austin and San Diego, which have recently moved to eliminate parking minimums, have found that it improves housing affordability and access to transit. Parking lots take up 25% of the space in our city, and excessive parking requirements contribute to as much as $200 of your monthly rent. Many of these lots lie partly empty and the space can be better used to house families. Sign our petition to push Dallas to take this same step, and share it with your friends! 

Petition: Elimination Parking Minimums for Dallas.

We are demanding that the City Planning Commission and the City of Dallas move to:

1) Eliminate the parking minimum requirements, with no exemptions from the current bill. 

 2) These spaces in the future should be used to build affordable housing and create green spaces. 

The Issue:

In Texas there are many places, specifically in Dallas, that require an excessive amount of parking spaces to be available for each living areas, businesses or play areas. Recently, many citizens and experts have questioned if these mandates are still needed. Parking minimums have been the same in Texas for decades based on old, no longer accurate needs. Many of the parking spaces in our city stand empty, which is a poor use of precious space. We are now taking action to ensure that the city of Dallas catches up to the new needs of Dallas on parking minimums. We are demanding a change in these outdated mandates and to utilize this space instead to address housing affordability crisis, improve transportation accessibility, build green spaces and more. This doesn't mean that parking or driving will go away. It means that a Wal-mart, for example, doesn't need a parking lot of 1,000 spaces, which is rarely ever at full capacity. That space can be better used for other purposes, and should be used according to the pressing needs of Dallas' citizens. 

The Solution:
We demand the the City Planning Commission vote this fall to eliminate the parking minimum requirements. This bill has gotten through multiple rungs of city government, and now it falls upon the members of CPC to take a step forward for a better Dallas. Many developers fall victim to provide unnecessary parking  due to the restrictions placed on them by the City of Dallas requirements. These restrictions can correlate to an increase in mortgage prices and renting, which directly affect financially the people you serve. This does not mean parking will be completely removed. We still understand federally certain parking spaces for disabled and people still are required to a certain aspect. Eliminating unnecessary parking mandates will also increase the usage of public transit, biking and walking as commuting options, and incentives for improving transit architecture are outlined in the parking minimums bill. This decision will have positive effect on the road to Dallas becoming more green and affordable for all.

Note: This petition does not have a date! We had to insert one for the website, but there is no actual event in November - just fill out your info to sign the petition.

**Join us at the next Allegheny County Board of Health (BOH) meeting to demand that all new fracking be prohibited in Allegheny County.**

Just as recently as 2023, a state-funded health study in southwest PA found that fracking correlates with increased rates of asthma and low birth weight, as well as sharply elevated risk of childhood lymphoma _(5-7 times the national average)_.

Per the Pennsylvania Disease and Prevention Control Act of 1955, "Local boards and departments of health shall be primarily responsible for the prevention and control of communicable and non-communicable disease... in accordance with the regulations of the board and subject to the supervision and guidance of the department." *This means that the Allegheny County BOH is responsible for and has the power to enact policy to prevent the incredibly harmful effects of fracking!*

title: Reconstruction of Francis Johnson’s New Cotillions

sponsor.name: The New York Baroque Dance Company

description:
The keystone of our project will be a fresh and thrilling look at the cotillions and other popular dances by this little known African American composer from Philadelphia, Francis Johnson (1792-1844).  Dances to be included are the “Pas de châle” (shawl), a Spanish dance, a hornpipe, a 19th Century minuet and a waltz. Beginning already in the 1790s, Americans were fond of the fandango and other Spanish dances. Francis Johnson, who never visited Spain, composed at least three Spanish Dances, probably intended for a young lady playing castanets. The music we have selected for our “Pas de châle” was composed by Francis Johnson for Mrs. Wallack, a principal dancer of the Chestnut Street Theatre.

 

Johnson’s suite of cotillions is extraordinary for several reasons. Not only is it possible to pinpoint the exact day that and even the precise hour that they were first performed in Philadelphia, we know that the performance was charged with especially strong emotion, as the original dancers and spectators all shared a warm and very sincere gratitude to the Marquis de Lafayette for his role in American Independence. Our musical source is from the Farewell Tour of America by General Lafayette in 1824 and contains not only the works performed that evening in the Chestnut Street Theatre, but also includes precious annotations on these dances’ spatial paths and the dance steps. These instructions, unattributed, seem to be by the composer, Francis Johnson, which would make them the first published choreographies by a person of color. Moreover, the musical source, supplemented by early newspapers, clarifies how the preceding march unfolded, with Lafayette’s entrance, the formation of a “haie d’honneur,” etc. 

 

Our project is important to dance scholars and the American and French general public alike, because of its relevance, rarity and diverse cultural significance. In addition to reminding audiences of the crucial role of France in American Independence and the importance of French culture in American dance, theater, fashion, and social life, it will shine a much needed light on this African American composer whose talent is largely overlooked today and deserves to be celebrated in our time. 

 

These ball and salon dances will be emerging from careful research derived from sources of the time including Thomas Wilson’s A Description of the Correct Method of Waltzing (1817) and two rare manuscripts at the Library of the Paris Opera: Jean-Etienne Despréaux’s Terpsi-Coro-Graphie (1815) and the anonymous Chorégraphie de divers ballets réglés sans doute au Collège de Montaigu (s.d.). 

 

The dance steps will be realized according to a Philadelphia treatise by Victor Guillou (Elements and Principles of the Art of Dancing, Philadelphia, 1817), which is based on a work by Jean-Henri Gourdoux-Daux (Principes et notions élémentaires sur l’art de la danse, Paris, 1811). This Franco-American treatise details the dance technique used in cotillions in this period.

 

Awarded Research Grant

We are able to properly reconstruct dances from this period thanks to the expertise of long-time NYBDC collaborator Alan Jones, whose thirty years of experience conducting research in the dance technique and repertory of the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries makes him an essential collaborator to a dance program involving this repertoire. The New York Baroque Dance Company’s Julia Bengtsson and Alan Jones have been awarded a grant from the French Ministry of Culture through The Centre National de la Danse which is supporting their research for this project.

 

ON THE STAGE!

 

We are grateful to the French government for supporting the research stage of this project. Now it is time for the United States government and its people to support the productions costs of rehearsals with the artists, costumes, transportation and space rentals for workshops and performances. We need your help!


Checks can also be made out to The New York Baroque Dance Company Inc. and mailed to:
The New York Baroque Dance Company c/o Rachel List
141 East Third Street #2D
New York, NY 10009.
